  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Visiting Plum Forest Temple, Following the Rhyme
  author: Kim Heun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    With idle heart I carry my seat upon the water,
    Returning once more to seek the Brahmin's temple.
    Bamboo shoots push forth their tender sheaths anew,
    While tidal waters wash away the ancient marks.
    Clouds and sunset glow conceal the Buddha hall,
    Smoke and mist divide me from the fishing village.
    I borrow but a mat to rest my weary form—
    This stillness washes clean my turbid, clouded mind.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Brahmin's temple' (바라문) refers to the Buddhist monastery, using Sanskrit terminology common in classical Korean poetry.
    - The poem employs the technique of 'following the rhyme' (차운), composing new verses that echo the rhyme scheme of an earlier poem.
    - The imagery of bamboo shoots and tidal marks suggests the cyclical renewal of nature and the impermanence of earthly traces.
